# Clean Code — Pragmatic Standards

## Core principles

- Prefer the **smallest change that works** (KISS/YAGNI).
- Keep each function focused (SRP); split only when it clarifies intent.
- Remove duplication when it meaningfully reduces complexity (DRY).
- Leave the codebase cleaner than you found it (Boy Scout rule).

## Naming

- Names must reveal intent. If you need a comment to explain a name, **rename it**.
- Function names are **verb + noun** (`fetchResources`, `computeRollup`, `formatK`).
- Boolean names read like questions: `isLoading`, `hasRouting`, `canEdit`, `shouldRefetch`.
- Use `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for constants that are truly constant across the module.

## Functions

- Prefer **small functions**; avoid “do-everything” blocks.
- Prefer **0–2 parameters**. If you need more, use a single options object.
- Avoid surprising side effects. Don’t mutate inputs unless it’s clearly expected by the type/API.
- Keep one level of abstraction per function (don’t mix parsing + I/O + formatting in one body).

## Structure

- Use **guard clauses**; keep the happy path last.
- Prefer flat code over deep nesting (avoid nesting beyond 2 levels).
- Compose small helpers rather than building “god functions”.
- Co-locate code with its usage; avoid dumping single-use helpers into generic `utils`.

## Comments (only when they add information)

- Delete obvious comments and commented-out code.
- Comments may explain **why** (constraints/trade-offs) — not what the code already states.

## Before editing a file

- Check what imports this module and what it imports.
- If you change a signature or contract, update dependents in the **same** change.
